<Base title="Quick Start" description="From zero to a scaffolded substrate project in under five minutes.">
  <h1>Quick Start</h1>
  <p>From zero to a scaffolded substrate project in under five minutes.</p>

  <h2>1. Scaffold your project</h2>
  <p>From your repo root:</p>
  <pre><code>npx @op4z/substrate@latest init --bridge claude</code></pre>
  <p>This creates:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>substrate.config.json</code> at the repo root.</li>
    <li><code>auto/</code> with the seven canonical subdirectories
      (<code>commands</code>, <code>instructions</code>, <code>scripts</code>,
      <code>config</code>, <code>standards</code>, <code>audits</code>,
      <code>docs</code>).</li>
    <li><code>auto/.substrate-manifest.json</code> tracking every scaffolded file.</li>
    <li><code>.claude/commands/substrate.md</code> for the Claude Code slash command.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>2. Add an audit (v1 surface)</h2>
  <pre><code>npx substrate add audit backend</code></pre>
  <p>
    Drops <code>auto/instructions/main/audit-backend.md</code> into your repo.
    Edit it — it's yours now. Substrate reads from your copy at runtime.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Run the audit</h2>
  <pre><code>npx substrate audit --type backend</code></pre>
  <p>
    Or run the detector runtime directly against <code>RULES.yaml</code>:
  </p>
  <pre><code>npx substrate audit                  # all rules
npx substrate audit --rule BE-PY-001  # one rule
npx substrate audit --diff            # ripgrep detectors on staged diff only</code></pre>

  <h2>4. Try the v2 workflow runtime</h2>
  <p>
    Once v2 ships, you can author a workflow manifest at
    <code>substrate/workflows/&lt;id&gt;.yaml</code> + a body at
    <code>substrate/workflows/&lt;id&gt;.body.md</code>. Reference templates
    ship under the package's <code>templates/workflows/</code> — copy one
    out:
  </p>
  <pre><code># Validate the manifest
npx substrate validate substrate/workflows/tackle-task.yaml

# Plan steps without executing (dry-run)
npx substrate run tackle-task --dry-run

# Execute end-to-end
npx substrate run tackle-task</code></pre>

  <h2>5. Inspect what substrate would load</h2>
  <p>
    The deterministic <code>substrate query *</code> surface lets you
    introspect context without running a workflow:
  </p>
  <pre><code>npx substrate query rules --by-prefix "BE-PY-*"
npx substrate query standards --pattern "backend/*.md"
npx substrate query memory --types feedback --tags ai-workflow
npx substrate query doc-checks --for-files "src/foo.ts" --commit-message "feat: add foo"
npx substrate query sessions --workflow tackle-task --limit 10</code></pre>

  <h2>6. Run via Claude Code</h2>
  <p>In Claude Code, type:</p>
  <pre><code>/substrate audit --type backend
/substrate run tackle-task</code></pre>
  <p>
    The slash command dispatches to the same CLI, loading the
    workflow's manifest + body into Claude's context so it produces
    the AI-guided execution.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Upgrade as substrate evolves</h2>
  <pre><code>npx substrate upgrade --check       # See what's drifted
npx substrate upgrade --apply       # Walk modified entries interactively</code></pre>
  <p>
    For modified files, substrate shows you a three-way diff (original
    template → your current copy → new template) and lets you choose
    <em>keep / take-new / merge / eject</em>.
  </p>

